{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"23ae4c8e-53a6-471b-8a51-3fbe79879d72","content":"There's no relevant documentation in this repository, but here's the general approach for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash reports**\n   macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** (before the crash):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Core files are disabled by default on macOS.\n\n3. **Check for existing cores**:\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   macOS may write to `/cores/core.<pid>` if enabled.\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **SIP considerations**: System Integrity Protection can prevent core dumps for certain processes. If needed, check with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT**: Since `createdump` is a .NET runtime tool not bundled with NativeAOT, you rely on OS-level mechanisms (steps above) rather than .NET-specific tooling.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22b06020-cb65-4c63-a9f1-4b48a431c035","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository appears to be empty or doesn't contain relevant documentation about this topic. Let me answer from my general knowledge about macOS crash dumps for NativeAOT apps.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"DA08:2F4A2A:230A4E4:26C4886:6A03D8E5"},"id":"e4527cd4-1c72-4132-a6c4-476cd67d3bc6","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:50:39.857Z","parentId":"af3d78c9-908f-450f-9d7d-4657786e9818"}
